Chapter 2 Data Preprocessing¶

Data preprocessing is the process of transforming raw data into a clean, consistent, and well-structured format suitable for building predictive models and machine learning algorithms. As the first and one of the most critical steps in the modeling pipeline, it directly influences model accuracy, efficiency, and overall performance.

a. Data Cleaning and Formatting¶

It is essential to clean the data, correct inconsistencies, and organize it into a properly formatted structure before applying any modeling techniques.

b. Handling Missing Values¶

Missing values can bias results or reduce efficiency. Strategies include:

  • Imputation (mean/median/mode replacement, regression methods, KNN imputation)
  • Removing incomplete records (if appropriate)

c. Normalization and Scaling¶

Numerical features often need to be scaled to ensure fair contribution in model training. For example:

  • MinMaxScaler rescales each feature to lie within [0, 1].
  • This is particularly effective when features are on very different scales and when using algorithms sensitive to feature magnitude (e.g., k-nearest neighbors, neural networks).

Terminology: Independent variables are also referred to as predictors or features.

d. Encoding Categorical Variables (Dummy Variables)¶

Categorical variables must be converted into numeric form for most machine learning algorithms.

  • A dummy variable assigns a numeric code (0 or 1) to indicate category membership.
  • Each category of the original feature becomes a new binary variable.

e. Feature Engineering and Selection¶

  • Feature engineering: creating new features from existing ones (e.g., binning continuous variables, generating polynomial features).
  • Feature selection: choosing the most relevant predictors automatically or manually to reduce noise and improve generalization.

f. Handling Non-Normality¶

Some models assume normality of features. Transformations such as:

  • Power transformation
  • Box-Cox transformation

These methods can help stabilize variance and approximate normality.

g. Dimensionality Reduction¶

Techniques like Principal Component Analysis (PCA) reduce the number of features while preserving most of the data’s variance. This improves computational efficiency and reduces overfitting.

h. Learned Embeddings¶

For complex data types such as text, learned embeddings (e.g., word embeddings from deep learning models) provide dense, informative numerical representations. They are dense, low-dimensional vector representations of high-dimensional or categorical data, where the values are automatically learned by a machine learning model rather than manually engineered. They capture semantic or structural relationships between data points, making them highly useful for predictive modeling.

Case Study: Cell Segmentation in High-Content Screening¶

The segmentationOriginal dataset from the AppliedPredictiveModeling package is a well-known example for image segmentation classification tasks.

  • Context: The dataset arises from high-content screening experiments, where automated imaging is used to capture and analyze cells.
  • Predictors: It includes a wide range of variables derived from cell images, such as shape, texture, and intensity measurements.
  • Response Variable: Each observation is labeled as either "PS" (well-segmented) or "WS" (poorly segmented), indicating the quality of the cell segmentation.

This dataset serves as a benchmark for developing and testing predictive models in biomedical image analysis.

The sample skewness = $$ \frac{\sum (x_i- \bar {x})^3} {n s^3} $$

If the sample skewness is close to zero, maybe the data are symmetrical.

If the sample skewness is much bigger than zero, the data are postively skewed/skewed to the right.

If the sample skewness is much below than zero, the data are negatively skewed/skewed to the left.

In [8]:
#Self defined function in R:
#To find the skewness of a variable x
  skewfun = function(x)
  {  
     xbar = mean(x)
     s = sd(x)
     n = length(x)
     sk = sum((x - xbar)^3)/(n*s^3)
     return(sk)  
  }

 
#To find the skewness of SkewIntenCh1 using skewfun
  round(skewfun(segmentationOriginal$ SkewIntenCh1), 2)
  
#To find skewness of NeighborAvgDistCh1           
  round(skewfun(segmentationOriginal$ NeighborAvgDistCh1), 2)

Output: The skewness statistic measures the asymmetry of the distribution of x.

Interpretation:

Skewness ≈ 0 → distribution is roughly symmetric.

Positive skewness → long right tail.

Negative skewness → long left tail.

Power transfomation¶

Box-Cox transformation is a data science technique to transform a variable so that it resembles a normal distribution.

Plot the data/calcualte the skewness to see if the distribution of variables

Formula:¶

$$ Y = \left \{ \begin{array}{l} { { \frac{X ^ \lambda - 1 } \lambda } \ \textrm{ for } \lambda \neq0, } \\ { { \mathop{\rm log} } X \ \textrm{ for } \lambda = 0. } \end{array} \right . $$

Package MASS¶

package caret¶

library(MASS)
#Run boxcox transformation
yval = segmentationOriginal$EqEllipseProlateVolCh1
out = boxcox(yval ~ 1)

#To get the lambda to max the likelihood function as in the plot
lambda = out$x[out$y==max(out$y)]
lambda 

#The power transformation (without )
x.new =  yval^(lambda)           # the box-cox transformation
hist(x.new)

The Yeo–Johnson transformation¶

The Yeo–Johnson transformation is a power transformation technique designed to make data more normally distributed. Like the Box–Cox transformation, it aims to stabilize variance and reduce skewness, thereby improving the performance and accuracy of statistical models. Unlike Box–Cox, however, the Yeo–Johnson method can also handle zero and negative values, making it more broadly applicable. By making data distributions more symmetric and closer to normal, this transformation enhances interpretability and model fit.

The Yeo–Johnson transformation:

$$ T(x;\lambda) = \begin{cases} \frac{(x+1)^{\lambda} - 1}{\lambda}, & \text{if } x \geq 0, \, \lambda \neq 0, \\[8pt] \ln(x+1), & \text{if } x \geq 0, \, \lambda = 0, \\[12pt] -\frac{(-x+1)^{2-\lambda} - 1}{2-\lambda}, & \text{if } x < 0, \, \lambda \neq 2, \\[8pt] -\ln(-x+1), & \text{if } x < 0, \, \lambda = 2. \end{cases} $$

where

  • $x$ is the original data value (can be negative, zero, or positive),
  • $\lambda$ is the transformation parameter estimated from the data.

Find nearZero variance predictors¶

A nearZero variance predictor: if the variance is close to zero, the data values may be the same for most cases. All data values are the same : zero variance (almost zero variance if most of the values are the same, except a very few are different). Sometimes, the data may have predictors that only have a single unique value or might have only a few unique values that occur with exetreme low frequencies, which may cause some models to crash or the fit to be unstable.

function nearZeroVar ( caret) Return the column numbers of any near-zero variance predictors

To identify these predictors, the following:

  • the frequency of the most prevalent value over the second most frequent value (called the "frequency ratio''), which would be near one for well-behaved predictors and very large for highly-unbalanced data.

  • the "percent of unique values'' is the number of unique values divided by the total number of samples that approaches zero as the granularity (the level of details) of the data increases.

If the frequency ratio is greater than a pre-specified threshold and the unique value percentage is less than a threshold, we might consider a predictor to be near zero-variance.

Example: nR11 varialbe in R dataset "mdrr" from caret package.

Identify Highly Correlated Predictors¶

While there are some models that thrive on correlated predictors such as pls, many models may benefit from reducing the level of correlation between the predictors.

Correlation: $r$ (sample correlation)

To detect highly correlated predictors, func-tion "findCorrelation" returns column numbers denoting the predictors that are recommended for deletion.

In [22]:
correlations = cor(segData)
dim(correlations)

#To make a correlation plot
library(corrplot)
corrplot(correlations, order = "hclust")

#To find Highly Correlated Predictors with cutoff value 0.9
#returns the col numbers of variables which have high correlation values
highCorr = findCorrelation(correlations, cutoff = .90)

#Delete all variables which have a high correlation. 
filteredSegData = segData[, -highCorr]

Transformation - standarization , scaling, normalization, ...¶

Sacling the data so that each feature is in the range [0,1]. It works well when the features have different scales and the algorithm being used is sensitive to the scale of the features, such as k-nearest neighbors or neural networks.

Scaling and centering for an individual predictor: $z = \frac{(x- \bar {x})} {s}$ where x is a data value.

  scaled.x = scale(x, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)

Data Transformations for Multiple Predictors¶

The purpose of these transformations is to address outliers and reduce the dimensionality of the data: two essential steps for enhancing both the performance and interpretability of statistical and machine learning models.

Transformations to Mitigate Outliers¶

For models that are highly sensitive to outliers, the spatial sign transformation can be applied. This approach reduces the influence of extreme values by focusing on the direction of the data rather than its magnitude:

$$ x_{ij}^* = \frac{x_{ij}}{\sqrt{\sum_j x_{ij}^2}} $$

Here, each observation vector is rescaled to unit length, effectively projecting the data onto the unit sphere in the feature space.

Data Reduction and Feature Extraction¶

Data reduction techniques aim to create a smaller set of predictors while retaining most of the information contained in the original variables. By lowering the overall data complexity, these methods simplify the model and often improve interpretability.

Example: The spatial sign transformation (Serneels et al., 2006) projects predictors onto the unit circle in (p)-dimensional space by dividing each vector by its Euclidean norm. Before applying this transformation, predictors must be centered and scaled to ensure comparability.

Missing Values¶

If the pattern of missing data is related to the outcome, it is known as "informative missingness." This type of missingness can introduce significant bias into the model, as the missing data itself provides valuable information about the outcome.

In R, we can use the mice package (Multiple Imputation by Chained Equations) to perform both multiple imputation and the subsequent analysis. The mice() function carries out the imputation using chained equations. Without delving too deeply into the details, chained equations are a variant of the Gibbs Sampler, an MCMC (Markov Chain Monte Carlo) method. This approach iterates between estimating missing values and estimating parameters for the distribution of the variables, with both being conditional on the other variables. The number of imputations is controlled by the m argument, and the default value is set to 5.

Package Caret knnImpute function:

The knnImpute method from the caret package employs the k-nearest neighbors (k-NN) algorithm to impute missing values. The k-NN algorithm predicts missing values by using data from other variables with similar (non-missing) values in the dataset. One of the advantages of the caret package is that it automatically standardizes the data before applying k-NN, as the developers note that standardization typically leads to more accurate results.

To create the imputation model for predicting missing values, we use the preProcess() function. This function takes the dataset and the desired imputation method, which in this case is set to "knnImpute", to perform the necessary calculation

In [17]:
library(caret)

# Median imputation
pp_median <- preProcess(dat["ca"], method = "medianImpute")
dat_ca_median <- predict(pp_median, dat["ca"])

# Mean imputation
pp_mean <- preProcess(dat["ca"], method = "meanImpute")
dat_ca_mean <- predict(pp_mean, dat["ca"])


#set.seed(253)
# Load the package if not
pre.model = preProcess(dat, "knnImpute")
#the data
imputed.pred = predict(pre.model, dat)
#Note: knnImpute expects all predictors to be numeric, and it will standardize variables internally before imputing. If you only pass one variable (dat$ca), KNN won’t have neighbors to learn from. Usually, you pass the whole dataset (all numeric columns), and KNN imputes missing values jointly.

Dummy variables¶

A dummy variable, also known as an indicator, dichotomous, discrete, or categorical variable, is a numeric value used to represent a categorical variable, such as gender or race. They take on values of 0 or 1, where each value indicates the presence or absence of a specific category.
